By
Willard Spiegelman
Updated Nov. 27, 2012 5:58 p.m. ET
Philadelphia Today's plutocrats collect art, often big art. Millions of dollars are commonplace for works by Picasso, Pollock, Rothko, Warhol, the usual suspects. Books—those smaller objects one can hold and read, as well as admire for beauty and value—have attracted the attention and the money of wealthy collectors (most all of them men) ever since Johannes Gutenberg
began the revolution of movable type six centuries ago. Times change. Bookmen may now be going the way of bookstores—witness Larry McMurtry's
summer sale in Archer City, Texas, which sold off most of the inventory of his used-books store there to other dealers from all over the country—and books themselves may soon become a quaint, disposable part of cultural history. It was not always thus. Many gentlemen (think of J.P. Morgan) had libraries. Enlarge Image
A.S.W. Rosenbach's library.
Susan Beard Design One is here, at 2008-2010 Delancey Place, off Rittenhouse Square, the part of William Penn's
"green country town" resembling a larger version of New York's West Village. In the middle of a block of four-story 19th-century row houses shaded by towering sycamore, locust and maple trees stands the Rosenbach Museum & Library, the 1954 legacy of two bachelor brothers whose collections, especially the books, are nothing short of amazing. Philip Rosenbach
(1863-1953) specialized in decorative arts, paintings and furniture. His younger brother, A.S.W. (1876-1952)—with a 1902 doctorate from the University of Pennsylvania and a dissertation about the influence of Cervantes on Shakespeare
—was the bookman. Their Uncle Moe had a bookshop, which A.S.W. took over. A.S.W. Rosenbach thought that American scholars should not have to travel to great European libraries to pursue their research, so he started to buy works for resale to collectors and collections. Rosenbach Co. had branches in Manhattan and Philadelphia and, for the first half of the 20th century, was this country's most important purveyor of books and manuscripts. Today the museum occupies adjacent townhouses, the second purchased in 1993 to augment exhibition space. It is filled with mostly 18th-century English and American furniture and portraits, plus such miscellaneous pieces as King Charles II's
document chest, Herman Melville's
bookcase, Robert Burns's
powder horn and Lord Byron's
calling-card case. It is the library holdings that truly astonish. The Americana begins with materials from the age of discovery: letters of Hernán Cortés
and Francisco Pizarro
; the first books printed in this hemisphere, in Mexico (1543) and Peru (1584); and the Bay Psalm Book, the first book printed in the American colonies (Cambridge, 1661). Among the British works: early editions and manuscripts of Chaucer, a rare first edition of John Bunyan's
"Pilgrim's Progress"; the largest collection of Robert Burns outside Edinburgh; Charles Dickens's
manuscripts of "Pickwick Papers" and "Nicholas Nickleby." The list goes on. Pride of place belongs to the manuscript of James Joyce's
"Ulysses" (purchased in 1924), and to 80% of Joseph Conrad's
manuscripts (the bulk of which was purchased in 1923). Most prominently and popularly displayed are the the works of two artists who knew each other: Marianne Moore and Maurice Sendak. The great American poet died in 1972. Sendak, her neighbor in Greenwich Village, had persuaded her to sell her papers to the Rosenbach, which she did on the condition that it also install the parlor of her apartment in the library. And here we have it: her furniture; her animal figurines and works of art; her typewriter; her baseballs signed by Yogi Berra and Mickey Mantle, as well as an exercise bar hanging over a closet door. The museum is now celebrating Sendak himself, who died earlier this year, with a display of paintings, illustrations and editions from throughout his long career. He began giving things to the Rosenbach in 1968; it now holds more than 10,000 of Sendak's items. In a downstairs gallery we find original drawings from the best-selling "Where the Wild Things Are" and "The Night Kitchen," as well as Sendak's pen-and-ink illustrations of I.B. Singer
stories and etchings for William Blake's
"Songs of Innocence." The Sendak display continues through May 26, 2013. In another downstairs parlor there's a framed letter to A.S.W. Rosenbach from Harry Elkins
Widener, dated March 19, 1912, from London. Four weeks later young Harry set sail. On the Titanic. He was the one who put Rosenbach on the map. He patronized the bookstore and began collecting. After his death, his mother endowed, in his memory and name, Harvard's encyclopedic library. A.S.W. Rosenbach was the agent for all this. He also managed collections for what became the Folger Shakespeare Library in Washington and the Huntington Library in San Marino, Calif. Closer to home, he developed a long personal and professional relationship with Lessing Rosenwald, the Sears Roebuck magnate from Chicago who moved to Philadelphia and assembled a great collection that went ultimately to the Library of Congress and the National Gallery of Art. On the crisp fall day I visited, a docent gave a tour to me and two suburban ladies, one an aspiring memoirist enrolled in a creative-writing program on Philadelphia's Main Line. As we finished, another quartet of tourists wandered in. Upstairs in the library, a Japanese scholar pored over Joyce materials, and a married couple in town for an academic conference had just rushed in from the airport to see a letter of Moore's. Another Moore aficionado—also a nascent poet—came to pay her homage. Intimacy and informality prevailed. To handle scholarly materials, the Rosenbach requires not the usual white gloves demanded by other libraries but a good old-fashioned hand-washing (latex can do more damage to delicate paper than clean, oil-free hands). I couldn't resist asking to see and touch one piece that stopped my heart and brought tears to my professorial eyes. It was the manuscript whose purchase got A.S.W. Rosenbach started on the final, and greatest, chapter of his buying career. In London in 1885 Sotheby's had sold at auction the manuscripts of six letters of John Keats.
Oscar Wilde,
enraged by the salacious intermingling of art and commerce, wrote a protest sonnet. Thirty-five years later, at Manhattan's Anderson Galleries, Rosenbach bought the poet's penultimate letter to Fanny Brawne, his fiancée, dated July 5, 1820, before his departure for Italy, where he died of tuberculosis seven months later. The great poet was also a typical, temperamental 24-year-old young man who, finding his girlfriend flirting with his roommate, wrote to her with envy, jealousy, rage and sadness, "I will resent my heart having been made a football." I couldn't put a price on the letter. Mr. Spiegelman, editor-in-chief of the Southwest Review, grew up in Philadelphia. Email
