By
Nancy DeWolf Smith
Updated March 17, 2006 11:59 p.m. ET
(See Corrections & Amplifications item below.) "The Evidence," ABC's new crime drama, deserves an award for packing the most intrigue into a first episode (Wednesday, 10-11 p.m. ET). I'm not talking about the plot, which unravels in a satisfying way, but the regular cast. It doesn't happen very often that halfway into the pilot for a new show, you're already looking forward to subsequent episodes just to find out more about the characters you've glimpsed in the first few minutes. In this case, the objects of fascination not only include the two main detective partners -- a serious Rob Estes and a laid-back Orlando Jones, playing perfectly off each other on the streets of San Francisco. Even the people who make relatively brief appearances leave you wanting to know more about them, e.g., Martin Landau as a slightly spooky forensic lab chief. And what about his gorgeous British assistant, or the beat cop who looks like a vampire with her hair down and seems to have a thing for one of the detectives? What makes them tick and what will they get up to down the road? If the first episode is any indication, solving each week's case will always be a trip, too. The show's opening device includes Mr. Landau in voice-over, introducing a victim and reviewing the evidence with which the detectives will begin. This week, it's the body of a dead medical student, Laura Green, and several possible clues, like her cellphone, a locket and a severed finger with a tiny compass ring on it. With that on the table, we, the audience, join the crime solvers as they attempt to put the pieces together. As entertaining as that is, if "The Evidence" is a hit, this may be largely due to the chemistry between Rob Estes and Orlando Jones. The former, with his severe Lance Armstrong-style haircut, has a tragedy in his past -- a murdered wife -- which gives his character instant texture and depth, even when he's playing pranks on his partner. Mr. Jones's detective seems like the light-hearted part of the pair, and it falls to him to yank his partner back toward the light. But beneath the goofing around, he's an adult, too. In a scene at the end of the pilot, a bedridden Mr. Jones wolfs down a forbidden sandwich, smearing his face in the process. It's funny, but also touching because we have by now glimpsed a man in full bloom, and the more vulnerable he looks, the more we are reminded of how strong he is. All that in less than an hour. Amazing. The marvelous British actor Bill Nighy plays a man at the height of his powers in the television movie "Gideon's Daughter." (BBC America; due to a schedule change, now scheduled to debut on Saturday, March 25 from 8-10:15 p.m.) But the bloom is off his particular career rose. His character, Gideon Warner, is London's premier PR magician, sought after by show-business celebrities, government leaders and foreign media moguls who want guidance and image shaping from the maestro. This has made Gideon rich and famous, thronged everywhere he goes by powerful people eager to catch pearls of PR wisdom that seem to pour from his lips. Only Gideon is tired and bored and, worst of all, he feels like a Chauncey Gardiner -- the false seer of "Being There" -- with the added burden of knowing that the more people take him seriously, the more ridiculous both he and they are. Without moving a muscle, Mr. Nighy oozes elegant ennui. He also exudes a sadness so profound that it's palpable, especially after he attends a school-graduation performance by his college-bound daughter, Natasha (Emily Blunt). who warbles a haunting song about obsessive love and suicide. Things have gone irreparably wrong between father and beautiful daughter over the years, and in Gideon's mind is an overwhelming emotion that every parent will recognize: the fear that he will suffer the ultimate punishment of losing his child through death. Which bring us to the third element in this story, which concerns a pair of London parents whose son died in a traffic accident. Sorrow has driven the father mad. And the boy's mother, the now-divorced Stella (Miranda Richardson) is consumed by a grief greater than Gideon's, since his child is at least still living. Yet Stella has got some spark of life that draws Gideon to her in ways that may yet save them both. This is a movie that moves in mysterious ways, not with bangs or whimpers, but through an accumulation of tender sorrows that are never mawkish and eventually give way to glimmers of joy. For Mr. Nighy, it's a role far removed from the over-the-hill rock singer he played to such hilarious effect in "Love Actually." And then again, it isn't, because in both cases, the whole world outside seems to stop spinning whenever he's on screen. And now for something completely different, albeit also on BBC America. Starting tonight, 9-9:40 p.m., treat yourself to "High Spirits With Shirley Ghostman," the British psychic who communes with dead celebrities and holds the record for giving the most readings -- 22 -- in a single minute. It's all completely fake, of course, but not in the way of other psychic frauds. Shirley Ghostman is actually the comedian Marc Wootton who, in the manner of faux gangsta-journalist Ali G, impersonates a medium before an audience of people who have no idea that it's a joke. Goodness knows, they should. Each week, the lisping Mr. Ghostman, clad in a frilly white suit and sporting a blond mullet, starts his stage show -- set in a church -- by introducing the audience to his psychic helper, Sheba, a German shepherd. The sight of Sheba, whose picture is projected onto the wall of the church, ought to be enough to give the game away at the start, and some in the audience do smile. But nothing Mr. Ghostman does seems to entirely shatter the belief of the sort of people who would come to hear a psychic in the first place. Not even his readings directed at individual members of the crowd. When he looks at one and says, "You deserved that holiday, how were you supposed to know that dogs can't feed themselves?" the recipient looks stunned, even embarrassed, but not incredulous. Later in the show, a huffing and puffing Shirley suddenly channels a familiar spirit: "Hello, I am Lady Di, what died. I am coming to you from the other world, which I rule with my dear husband... Dodi Fayed. Thanks for the funeral, although I must tell you that the journey to Westminster Abbey was a little bit slow." When the camera cuts to members of the audience, some are trying not to giggle and some look like they are crying. Sure enough, even a finale that includes ghost images of Diana and Hitler playing rock music doesn't seem to have alerted some true believers in the audience to the enormity of the scam. In another segment of the program, Mr. Wootton is seen visiting a woman who appears to be a real "rumpologist," making a living reading people's bare backsides. In future episodes, Mr. Wootton will pose as a Polish rat catcher who now catches ghosts instead -- and some people might fall for that, too. All the more hilarious since right after "Shirley" ends on BBC America tonight, the WE channel is offering "John Edward Cross Country" (10-11 p.m.) featuring the stylings of a psychic who isn't trying to be funny at all, but whose basic gimmicks are eerily similar to Mr. Ghostman's. "Hollywood Science: Car Chases" (Sunday, 9-10 p.m.) reviews some of the movies' most-famous car capers and crashes -- from "Bullitt" and "The French Connection" to "Speed" and "The Fast and the Furious" -- and explains the laws of physics that were bent or broken to get them made. Fascinating stuff, especially when a design engineer reveals how hard it really is to make a car explode. Corrections & Amplifications: In this article, the network that will run "Hollywood Science: Car Chases" was omitted. It will air on the National Geographic Channel on Sunday at 9 p.m.
